om.%20She%20had%20chosen%20to%20have%20her%20maternal%20grandfather%20Samuel%20Kestenbaum%E2%80%99s%20number%20tattooed%20on%20her%20arm%2C%20but%20it%20was%20also%20for%20her%20maternal%20grandmother%2C%20Agi%20Kestenbaum.%20She%20had%20been%20in%20Auschwitz%20too%2C%20but%20was%20not%20tattooed%20because%20she%20was%20not%20expected%20to%20live.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELike%20Cohen%2C%20Weintraub%20Gilad%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20remember%20a%20specific%20time%20when%20she%20first%20noticed%20her%20grandfather%E2%80%99s%20number%2C%20but%20the%20stories%20about%20the%20Holocaust%20were%20a%20part%20of%20her%20life%20from%20childhood.%20She%20says%20her%20mother%2C%20who%20died%20eight%20years%20before%20we%20spoke%2C%20used%20to%20talk%20a%20lot%20about%20the%20Holocaust.%20%E2%80%9CShe%20knew%20everything%2C%E2%80%9D%20Weintraub%20Gilad%20says.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAll%20four%20of%20her%20grandparents%20had%20survived%20the%20Holocaust.%20Her%20paternal%20grandparents%20died%20when%20she%20was%20in%20her%20late%20teens%20and%20even%20now%2C%20she%20says%2C%20her%20father%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20talk%20about%20what%20they%20experienced.%20She%20says%20that%20when%20she%20asks%20her%20father%20questions%2C%20he%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20know%20the%20answers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWeintraub%20Gilad%20remains%20very%20close%20to%20her%20grandmother%2C%20who%20is%2095%20years%20old.%20The%20tattoo%20gives%20her%20the%20chance%20to%20continue%20what%20her%20mother%20used%20to%20do%20and%20talk%20about%20the%20Holocaust.%20%E2%80%9CIt%20starts%20the%20conversation%20and%20that%E2%80%99s%20the%20purpose%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20says%2C%20%E2%80%9Cthat%E2%80%99s%20the%20thing%20that%20my%20grandmother%20is%20so%20happy%20about.%20She%20knows%20that%20after%20she%E2%80%99s%20gone%2C%20that%20I%20will%20talk.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20tattoo%20itself%20features%20her%20grandfather%E2%80%99s%20number%20in%20a%20nest%20of%20leafy%20green%20vines.%20From%20different%20vines%20emerge%20letters%2C%20the%20initials%20of%20the%20names%20of%20Weintraub%20Gilad%E2%80%99s%20husband%20and%20her%20children.%20But%20the%20resulting%20composition%20is%20as%20much%20about%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20history%20as%20it%20is%20about%20their%20collective%20future.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20choice%20of%20green%20vines%20and%20leaves%20came%20from%20her%20love%20of%20nature.%20Her%20grandfather%E2%80%99s%20number%20was%20on%20his%20left%20arm%2C%20but%20Weintraub%20Gilad%20placed%20her%20own%20tattoo%20on%20her%20right%20arm.%20She%20says%20she%20wanted%20%E2%80%9Cto%20do%20it%20the%20same%20but%20different%E2%80%9D.%20One%20reason%20for%20choosing%20the%20right%20arm%20was%20because%20she%20did%20not%20want%20to%20see%20the%20number%20%E2%80%9Con%20the%20side%20of%20the%20heart%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThat%20same%20summer%2C%20I%20spoke%20with%20Yair%20Ron%20(Reisz)%2C%20also%20on%20Zoom.%20He%20grew%20up%20in%20Israel%2C%20on%20a%20kibbutz%20founded%20by%20Holocaust%20survivors.%20%E2%80%9CIt%20was%20a%20very%20small%20community%20of%20people%20with%20same%20idea%20of%20communism%2C%E2%80%9D%20he%20recalls.%20%E2%80%9CAll%20of%20them%20were%20Holocaust%20survivors%2C%20so%20all%20of%20them%20have%20numbers.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EGrowing%20up%2C%20no%20one%20on%20the%20kibbutz%20had%20grandparents%20or%20spoke%20about%20their%20suffering.%20Ron%E2%80%99s%20father%2C%20Jakub%20Reisz%20%E2%80%93%20whom%20everyone%20knew%20as%20Yakshi%20%E2%80%93%20said%20nothing%20about%20the%20Holocaust%20and%2C%20like%20many%20children%20of%20Holocaust%20survivors%2C%20Ron%20and%20his%20sister%20knew%20not%20to%20ask.%20Yakshi%20would%20talk%20about%20helping%20people%20escape%20from%20Slovakia%20to%20Hungary%20%E2%80%93%20but%20he%20never%20said%20a%20word%20about%20what%20he%20had%20experienced.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20was%20impossible%20to%20have%20a%20conversation%20about%20the%20Holocaust%20with%20my%20father.%20We%20were%20afraid%20to%20ask%20and%20afraid%20to%20hear.%20Maybe%20we%20didn%E2%80%99t%20want%20to%20hear.%20And%20he%20told%20us%20that%20he%20don%E2%80%99t%20want%20to%20tell%2C%20so%20we%20couldn%E2%80%99t%20exchange%20any%20information%20about%20the%20Holocaust%20whatsoever.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERon%20first%20noticed%20his%20father%E2%80%99s%20number%20as%20a%20child.%20Just%20as%20it%20was%20normal%20not%20to%20talk%20about%20things%20%E2%80%93%20about%20families%2C%20generations%2C%20loss%20%E2%80%93%20it%20was%20also%20normal%20to%20him%20and%20his%20peers%20that%20adults%20had%20numbers%20on%20their%20bodies.%20Until%20he%20started%20venturing%20out%20into%20the%20local%20town%20as%20a%20teenager%2C%20he%20didn%E2%80%99t%20really%20meet%20people%20from%20outside%20of%20the%20kibbutz%20%E2%80%93%20adults%2C%20that%20is%2C%20who%20didn%E2%80%99t%20have%20numbers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20seemed%20very%20natural%20to%20us%20that%20adults%20had%20numbers%20so%20we%20didn%E2%80%99t%20pay%20very%20much%20attention%20to%20this.%20We%20didn%E2%80%99t%20know%20other%20adults%20or%20people%20without%20numbers.%20The%20kibbutz%20was%20far%20away%20in%20the%20mountain%2C%20it%20was%20very%20isolated.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cfigure%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(min-width%3A%201466px)%20754px%2C%20(max-width%3A%20599px)%20100vw%2C%20(min-width%3A%20600px)%20600px%2C%20237px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26q%3D45%26auto%3Dformat%26w%3D754%26fit%3Dclip%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20man%20in%20a%20uniform%20holds%20up%20his%20arm.%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22600%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D45%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D600%26amp%3Bh%3D400%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D1%20600w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D30%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D600%26amp%3Bh%3D400%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D2%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D15%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D600%26amp%3Bh%3D400%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D3%201800w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D45%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D754%26amp%3Bh%3D503%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D1%20754w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D30%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D754%26amp%3Bh%3D503%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D2%201508w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570699%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240122-27-mssuh2.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26amp%3Bq%3D15%26amp%3Bauto%3Dformat%26amp%3Bw%3D754%26amp%3Bh%3D503%26amp%3Bfit%3Dcrop%26amp%3Bdpr%3D3%202262w%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22400%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EYair%20Ron%20bears%20his%20father%E2%80%99s%20number%20on%20his%20arm.%20Photo%3A%20John%20Jeffay%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cfigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20was%20only%20after%20Yakshi%E2%80%99s%20death%20that%20Ron%20started%20to%20piece%20together%20his%20story.%20Coming%20across%20a%20letter%20and%20diary%20that%20a%20friend%20of%20his%20father%E2%80%99s%20had%20written%2C%20Ron%20discovered%20that%20both%20men%20had%20been%20deported%20from%20Slovakia%20to%20Auschwitz.%20They%20had%20then%20been%20taken%20to%20Nazi-run%20work%20camps%2C%20from%20where%20they%20were%20eventually%20liberated.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAfter%20their%20release%2C%20they%20started%20their%20journey%20back%20to%20Slovakia%2C%20via%20Prague.%20To%20pass%20through%20the%20British%20military%20area%20without%20being%20detained%2C%20identification%20was%20required.%20Neither%20man%20had%20any%2C%20so%20they%20tattooed%20what%20looked%20like%20Auschwitz%20numbers%20on%20their%20left%20arms.%20Ron%20shared%20what%20he%20had%20learned%20with%20his%20family.%20They%20were%20very%20proud%20of%20Yakshi%2C%20he%20says%2C%20praising%20his%20%E2%80%9Ccreativity%20and%20thinking%20out%20of%20the%20box%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERon%20first%20thought%20about%20getting%20Yakshi%E2%80%99s%20number%20tattooed%20on%20his%20own%20body%20when%20he%20was%20around%2050%20years%20old%2C%20at%20the%20turn%20of%20the%20millennium.%20He%20discussed%20it%20with%20his%20father%20who%2C%20like%20most%20Holocaust%20survivors%2C%20was%20strongly%20opposed%20to%20the%20idea%20at%20first.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20says%20his%20relationship%20with%20his%20father%20was%20not%20an%20easy%20one.%20There%20were%20barriers%20between%20them.%20Ron%20ascribed%20these%2C%20in%20part%2C%20to%20Yakshi%E2%80%99s%20experiences%20of%20the%20Holocaust%20and%20the%20trauma%20he%20lived%20with.%20But%20it%20was%20more%20complex%20than%20that.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EKibbutzim%20in%20the%201950s%20and%201960s%2C%20like%20the%20one%20Ron%20grew%20up%20on%2C%20were%20often%20organised%20around%20collective-socialist%20principles.%20Until%20the%201980s%2C%20children%20were%20raised%20separately%20from%20their%20parents%20and%20slept%20in%20a%20communal%20children%E2%80%99s%20house.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC7753919%2F%5C%22%3EResearch%20has%20shown%3C%2Fa%3E%20variable%20attachment%20responses%20among%20those%20who%20grew%20up%20in%20this%20way%20%E2%80%93%20although%20it%20found%20little%20variation%20in%20attachment%20to%20fathers%2C%20compared%20with%20those%20who%20grew%20up%20in%20family%20homes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERon%20wonders%2C%20however%2C%20whether%20the%20fact%20that%20he%20and%20Yakshi%20did%20not%20enjoy%20a%20%E2%80%9Cnormal%E2%80%9D%20relationship%20is%20in%20some%20part%20due%20to%20growing%20up%20this%20way.%20Although%20he%20saw%20his%20father%20as%20a%20good%20man%2C%20the%20distance%20between%20them%20meant%20they%20could%20not%20speak%20about%2C%20as%20he%20puts%20it%2C%20%E2%80%9Creal%20feelings%20and%20thoughts%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHaving%20the%20number%20on%20his%20own%20body%2C%20Ron%20says%2C%20allowed%20him%20to%20reflect%20on%20what%20it%20is%20to%20live%20%E2%80%9Clike%20a%20numbered%20person%E2%80%9D.%20As%20survivors%20die%20out%2C%20he%20dwells%20on%20the%20thought%20that%20soon%20there%20will%20be%20no%20numbered%20people.%20This%2C%20to%20his%20mind%2C%20makes%20the%20number%20an%20important%20thing%20to%20keep%20%E2%80%93%20a%20tool%20for%20keeping%20the%20memory%20alive.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ETattooing%20in%20Auschwitz%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESerial%20number%20tattoos%20with%20symbols%2C%20shapes%20or%20letters%20were%20first%20introduced%20for%20prisoners%20in%20the%20Auschwitz%20concentration%20camp%20complex%20in%20October%201941.%20More%20than%20400%2C000%20people%20would%20be%20tattooed%20there.%20The%20exceptions%20were%20ethnic%20Germans%2C%20Austrians%2C%20police%20prisoners%20and%20Polish%20prisoners%20deported%20from%20Warsaw%20during%20the%201944%20uprising%20%E2%80%93%20plus%20Jewish%20prisoners%20held%20for%20a%20short%20time%20while%20waiting%20to%20be%20moved%20to%20other%20camps.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPrior%20to%20tattoos%2C%20identification%20numbers%20had%20been%20sewn%20on%20to%20the%20prison%20uniforms.%20Soviet%20prisoners%20of%20war%20were%20the%20first%20group%20to%20be%20tattooed%20after%20larger%20numbers%20started%20to%20die%20and%20the%20other%20prisoners%20took%20the%20deceased%E2%80%99s%20clothing%2C%20making%20it%20impossible%20to%20keep%20accurate%20records.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInitially%2C%20the%20tattoos%20were%20placed%20on%20the%20left%20side%20of%20each%20prisoner%E2%80%99s%20chest.%20Those%20who%20did%20the%20tattooing%20used%20a%20metal%20stamp%20with%20changeable%20plates%20fitted%20with%20needles%20that%20formed%20numbers%2C%20then%20rubbed%20blue%20ink%20into%20the%20bleeding%20holes.%20This%20technique%20enabled%20guards%20and%20prisoners%20to%20tattoo%20the%20number%20on%20a%20prisoner%E2%80%99s%20body%20in%20a%20single%20action.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%20the%20spring%20of%201942%2C%20all%20incoming%20Jewish%20prisoners%20selected%20for%20forced%20labour%2C%20rather%20than%20immediate%20death%2C%20were%20tattooed.%20In%20place%20of%20the%20metal%20plate%2C%20the%20tattooists%20now%20used%20a%20single%20needle%20to%20puncture%20the%20number%20into%20the%20prisoner%E2%80%99s%20skin%20by%20hand%2C%20then%20rubbed%20in%20the%20ink.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20numbers%20were%20tattooed%20on%20the%20prisoners%E2%80%99%20left%20forearms.%20Shapes%20and%20letters%20were%20sometimes%20also%20used%20to%20differentiate%20between%20groups%20of%20prisoners.%20Some%20Jewish%20prisoners%20had%20a%20triangle%20tattooed%20under%20their%20number.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fthe-genocide-of-the-roma-and-how-commemoration-of-this-forgotten-holocaust-is-shifting-92771%5C%22%3ERoma%20and%20Sinti%20prisoners%3C%2Fa%3E%20had%20the%20letter%20Z%20appended%20to%20their%20number%2C%20the%20first%20letter%20of%20the%20(pejorative)%20German%20word%20%3Cem%3EZigeuner%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20used%20at%20the%20time%20for%20these%20communities.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWith%20Hungarian%20Jews%20arriving%20in%20increasing%20numbers%2C%20new%20sequences%20of%20digits%20were%20introduced%20in%20May%201944.%20These%20began%20with%20the%20number%201%20and%20were%20prefaced%20first%20by%20the%20letter%20A%3B%20then%2C%20when%20more%20were%20needed%2C%20B.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20her%202001%20autobiographical%20book%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.co.uk%2Fbooks%2Fabout%2FStill_Alive.html%3Fid%3DNX5Fj8rLqkIC%26redir_esc%3Dy%5C%22%3EStill%20Alive%3A%20A%20Holocaust%20Girlhood%20Remembered%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20German%20studies%20scholar%20and%20Holocaust%20survivor%20Ruth%20Kl%C3%BCger%20describes%20the%20experience%20of%20getting%20forcibly%20tattooed%20in%20Auschwitz%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3E%5BAfter%20selection%5D%2C%20we%20got%20our%20ID%20numbers%20tattooed%20on%20our%20left%20arms.%20A%20few%20female%20prisoners%20had%20been%20installed%20outside%20the%20building%20at%20a%20table%20with%20the%20necessary%20equipment%20and%20we%20stood%20in%20line%2C%20waiting%20our%20turn.%20The%20women%20knew%20their%20job%2C%20they%20were%20very%20fast.%20At%20first%20it%20looked%20as%20if%20the%20black%20ink%20would%20easily%20wash%20off%2C%20and%20indeed%2C%20water%20took%20most%20of%20it%20away%2C%20but%20then%20the%20fine%20points%20of%20the%20number%20remained%3A%20A-3537.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EKl%C3%BCger%20speaks%20about%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20victims%E2%80%99%20skin%E2%80%9D%20saving%20the%20Nazis%20from%20having%20to%20%E2%80%9Cproduce%20dog%20tags%E2%80%9D.%20This%20underlines%20how%20dehumanising%20this%20Nazi%20practice%20of%20tattooing%20numbers%20on%20inmates%20was.%20As%20the%20Italian%20writer%20and%20Holocaust%20survivor%20Primo%20Levi%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.sagepub.com%2Fdoi%2Ffull%2F10.1177%2F07255136211042453%5C%22%3Eputs%20it%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20his%201986%20book%2C%20The%20Drowned%20and%20the%20Saved%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EIts%20symbolic%20meaning%20was%20clear%20to%20everyone%3A%20this%20is%20an%20indelible%20mark%2C%20you%20will%20never%20leave%20here%3B%20this%20is%20the%20mark%20with%20which%20slaves%20are%20branded%20and%20cattle%20sent%20to%20slaughter%2C%20and%20that%20is%20what%20you%20have%20become.%20You%20no%20longer%20have%20a%20name%3B%20this%20is%20your%20new%20name.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EAn%20embodied%20public%20memorial%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Auschwitz%20number%20has%20marked%20out%20those%20who%20survived%20by%20making%20them%20ever%20recognisable%20to%20others.%20It%20is%20this%20recognition%20that%20mattered%20so%20much%20to%20Rony%20Cohen%20in%20getting%20her%20own%20tattoo%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EI%20was%20proud%20to%20take%20my%20grandmother%20with%20me.%20To%20take%20her%20childhood%2C%20her%20missing%20her%20parents%20%E2%80%93%20those%20moments%20are%20in%20this%20number.%20Whenever%20someone%20sees%20it%2C%20they%20know%20this%20is%20Auschwitz.%20I%20want%20it%20to%20be%20noticed%20and%20understandable.%20No%20one%20should%20doubt%20what%20it%20is.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECohen%E2%80%99s%20grandmother%20and%20great%20uncle%20were%20of%20the%20cohort%20of%20siblings%20that%20have%20become%20known%20as%20%E2%80%9CMengele%20twins%E2%80%9D.%20The%20Nazi%20physician%20Josef%20Mengele%20had%20an%20interest%20in%20racial%20genetics.%20He%20first%20experimented%20on%20Roma%20and%20Sinti%20twins%20in%20what%20was%20known%20as%20the%20%E2%80%9CGypsy%20camp%E2%80%9D%20in%20Auschwitz-Birkenau%20%E2%80%93%20then%20on%20Jewish%20prisoners%20who%20he%20picked%20from%20the%20Theresienstadt%20camp-ghetto%20in%20Terez%C3%ADn%2C%20in%20the%20Protectorate%20of%20Bohemia%20and%20Moravia.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFrom%20May%201944%2C%20subjects%20for%20Mengele%E2%80%99s%20experiments%20were%20also%20picked%20from%20the%20unloading%20ramps%20at%20Auschwitz.%20Cohen%20recalled%20the%20story%20her%20grandmother%20had%20told%20her%2C%20about%20how%20she%20arrived%20in%20Auschwitz%20with%20her%20twin%20brother%2C%20aged%20eight%2C%20and%20her%20mother%20and%20aunts%20and%20all%20the%20other%20children%20of%20the%20family%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EThey%20saw%20the%20smoke%20from%20the%20crematorium.%20The%20family%20was%20walking%20and%20someone%20was%20saying%3A%20%E2%80%98Twins%2C%20twins%2C%20twins%20%E2%80%93%20where%E2%80%99s%20twins%3F%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInstead%20of%20hiding%20them%2C%20her%20mother%20said%20to%20her%20aunts%2C%20%E2%80%9CLet%E2%80%99s%20give%20them%20the%20twins%E2%80%9D.%20Her%20aunts%20thought%20she%20was%20crazy%20for%20suggesting%20that%20%E2%80%93%20but%20her%20mother%20thought%20she%20was%20saving%20her%20children.%20%E2%80%9CI%E2%80%99m%20going%20to%20save%20your%20life%20now%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20told%20her%20children.%20%E2%80%9CGive%20mummy%20a%20hug%20and%20you%E2%80%99re%20leaving%20now.%E2%80%9D%20This%20was%20the%20last%20moment%20Cohen%E2%80%99s%20grandmother%20could%20remember%20being%20with%20her%20mother.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHaving%20made%20it%20through%20selection%20and%20been%20forcibly%20tattooed%2C%20twins%20were%20sometimes%20given%20additional%20food%20which%20helped%20keep%20them%20alive.%20First-hand%20accounts%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcollections.ushmm.org%2Fsearch%2Fcatalog%2Fbib4007%5C%22%3Edescribe%3C%2Fa%3E%20how%20Mengele%20gave%20his%20victims%20chocolate%20before%20carrying%20out%20the%20most%20horrific%20experiments.%20He%20sewed%20twins%E2%80%99%20veins%20together%2C%20injected%20chemicals%20into%20testicles%20and%20spines%2C%20and%20inserted%20large%20needles%20into%20skulls.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%201994%20book%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcollections.ushmm.org%2Fsearch%2Fcatalog%2Fbib4007%5C%22%3EAnatomy%20of%20the%20Auschwitz%20Death%20Camp%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20chapter%20by%20historian%20Helena%20Kubica%20recounts%20the%20testimony%20of%20one%20man%2C%20Moshe%20Ofer%2C%20who%20was%20imprisoned%20with%20his%20twin%20brother.%20His%20testimony%20was%20collected%20by%20the%20Jerusalem%20tribunal%20that%20tried%20Mengele%20in%20absentia%20in%201985.%20Mengele%20killed%20Ofer%E2%80%99s%20brother%20with%20his%20experiments.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOfer%20describes%20how%2C%20after%20the%20experiments%2C%20the%20physician%20would%20bring%20gifts.%20The%20horror%20of%20that%20had%20never%20left%20him.%20%E2%80%9CEven%20today%2C%E2%80%9D%20he%20says%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20can%20see%20him%20entering%20through%20the%20door%20and%20I%20am%20paralysed%20with%20fear.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECohen%E2%80%99s%20grandmother%20similarly%20recalled%20Mengele%20bringing%20food%20for%20the%20twins.%20It%20saved%20them%20physically%2C%20she%20said%2C%20but%20the%20psychological%20damage%20was%20immeasurable.%20As%20Cohen%20puts%20it%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20grandmother%2C%20since%20the%20Holocaust%2C%20she%20has%20a%20sleeping%20disorder.%20In%20her%20dreams%2C%20her%20parents%20come%20and%20all%20the%20horror%20comes.%20She%20always%20tells%20me%3A%20%E2%80%98I%20can%E2%80%99t%20forgive%20myself%20that%20I%20remember%20Mengele%E2%80%99s%20face%20but%20I%20can%E2%80%99t%20remember%20my%20parents%E2%80%99%20faces.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHer%20brother%20%E2%80%93%20Cohen%E2%80%99s%20great%20uncle%20%E2%80%93%20had%20his%20tattoo%20removed%20after%20saving%20enough%20money.%20Her%20grandmother%2C%20by%20contrast%2C%20still%20bears%20it%20on%20her%20left%20arm.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAs%20a%20child%2C%20Cohen%20would%20ask%20questions.%20Sometimes%20her%20grandmother%20would%20make%20out%20that%20it%20was%20nothing.%20Sometimes%20she%E2%80%99d%20say%20she%20would%20tell%20her%20when%20she%20was%20older.%20Cohen%20describes%20herself%20as%20stubborn%20%E2%80%93%20she%20just%20kept%20asking.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhen%20she%20was%2012%20or%2013%2C%20for%20a%20school%20project%20on%20roots%2C%20she%20decided%20to%20do%20a%20video%20on%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20history.%20Cohen%20interviewed%20both%20her%20maternal%20grandparents.%20Her%20grandfather%20she%20describes%20as%20%E2%80%9Ctough%E2%80%9D%2C%20with%20%E2%80%9Call%20the%20characteristics%20of%20a%20typical%20survivor%E2%80%9D.%20He%20was%20keen%20that%20Cohen%20pass%20on%20all%20the%20information%20to%20her%20mother%20because%2C%20he%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CYour%20mum%20never%20asked.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECohen%20shared%20everything%20with%20her%20mother%20and%20her%20uncle%20%E2%80%93%20and%20it%20finally%20removed%20the%20elephant%20from%20the%20room.%20It%20made%20talking%20about%20the%20Holocaust%20possible.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAt%2017%2C%20like%20so%20many%20Israelis%2C%20Cohen%20went%20on%20a%20high-school%20visit%20to%20Poland%2C%20to%20the%20camps%20and%20the%20ghettos.%20Before%20leaving%20on%20this%20trip%2C%20she%20went%20to%20see%20her%20grandfather.%20He%20told%20her%20that%20going%20to%20Auschwitz%20would%20change%20everything%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20you%20stand%20there%20in%20those%20walls%20and%20you%20smell%20the%20death%20smell%20and%20you%20see%20the%20gas%20chamber%2C%20you%20will%20come%20back%20to%20Israel%20and%20you%20will%20tell%20me%3A%20%E2%80%98I%20can%E2%80%99t%20understand.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CI%20can%E2%80%99t%20understand%2C%E2%80%9D%20Cohen%20now%20says.%20%E2%80%9CMy%20grandfather%20was%20so%20right.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EHow%20Holocaust%20memorialisation%20has%20changed%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Auschwitz%20number%20tattoo%20was%20not%20always%20revered.%20After%20the%20second%20world%20war%2C%20survivors%20were%20often%20stigmatised.%20Public%20commemorations%20celebrated%20resistance%20and%20uprisings.%20The%20victims%20and%20survivors%2C%20by%20contrast%2C%20were%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tandfonline.com%2Fdoi%2Fabs%2F10.1080%2F02757206.2020.1726907%5C%22%3Eportrayed%20as%20weak%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThat%20early%20stigmatisation%20would%20follow%20some%20survivors%20throughout%20their%20lives%2C%20even%20when%20public%20perception%20started%20to%20shift.%20Some%2C%20like%20Cohen%E2%80%99s%20great%20uncle%2C%20had%20their%20number%20removed.%20Others%20covered%20it%20up%20with%20long%20sleeves.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFrom%20the%20early%201960s%2C%20as%20French%20historian%20Annette%20Wieviorka%20shows%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cornellpress.cornell.edu%2Fbook%2F9780801443312%2Fthe-era-of-the-witness%2F%23bookTabs%3D1%5C%22%3EThe%20Era%20of%20The%20Witness%3C%2Fa%3E%20(2006)%2C%20attitudes%20began%20to%20change%20%E2%80%93%20partly%20due%20to%20the%20testimonies%20heard%20during%20the%20trial%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.yadvashem.org%2Fholocaust%2Feichmann-trial%2Fabout.html%5C%22%3EAdolf%20Eichmann%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%201961-62.%20The%20author%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fmagazine%2F1963%2F02%2F16%2Feichmann-in-jerusalem-i%5C%22%3EHannah%20Arendt%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fmagazine%2Fa-reporter-at-large%2F02%2F23%2Feichmann-in-jerusalem-ii%5C%22%3Ereported%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fmagazine%2F1963%2F03%2F02%2Fiii-eichmann-in-jerusalem%5C%22%3Edistrict%20court%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fmagazine%2Fmjn-%3D1963%2F03%2F09%2Feichmann-in-jerusalem-iv%5C%22%3EJerusalem%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fmagazine%2F1963%2F03%2F16%2Feichmann-in-jerusalem-v%5C%22%3ENew%20Yorker%3C%2Fa%3E%20magazine%2C%20thereby%20giving%20survivor%20voices%20a%20global%20platform.%20The%20trauma%20that%20emerged%20from%20Eichmann%E2%80%99s%20trial%20reframed%20survival%20in%20itself%20as%20something%20heroic.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cfigure%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(min-width%3A%201466px)%20754px%2C%20(max-width%3A%20599px)%20100vw%2C%20(min-width%3A%20600px)%20600px%2C%20237px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570170%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240118-23-vfrt3z.jpg%3Fixlib%3Drb-1.1.0%26q%3D45%26auto%3Dformat%26w%3D754%26fit%3Dclip%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20black%20and%20white%20photograph%20of%20a%20court%20trial.%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22600%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fimages.theconversation.com%2Ffiles%2F570170%2Foriginal%2Ffile-20240118-23-vfr